<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-998-428  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 998 428.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lan Times  Dec 1989 v6 n12 p91(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Heavy sentences.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Price, Ron.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The computer industry and the legal community are both wrestlingwith the problem of determining the nature and severity ofcriminal sanctions against computer hackers who plant viruses incomputer networks.andP;  Two pending computer security laws, House Bill55 and Resolution 287, propose stiff penalties for convicted virushackers.andP;  Others favor a more moderate approach, arguing that thecrime should be regarded as a misdemeanor.andP;  They reason that it isundesirable to ruin someone's life and potential career with afelony conviction.andP;  Others take the position that the launching ofa computer virus is as much a criminal act as the bombing of anedifice.andP;  They suggest that a ten to fifteen year sentence isdesirable in order to take the deed out of the prank category andset an extreme example.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Legal IssuesComputer IndustryComputer CrimesHuman FactorsComputer Hackers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>